<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">NOTICE OF APPEAL</TI>
<P><BOLD>THE PLAINTIFF</BOLD> appeals to the Divisional Court from the verdict of the jury as accepted by the presiding trial judge, The Honourable Mr. Justice Myers, dated September 28, 2016, at the City of Toronto.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE APPELLANT ASKS:</BOLD></P>
<P>1) That the jury verdict be set aside and that a new trial be ordered.</P>
<P>2) In the alternative, that this Court issue judgment substituting its assessment of the plaintiff's damages.</P>
<P>3) That the respondents pay the appellant his costs of the trial and this appeal.</P>
<P>4) Such further and other relief as this Honourable Court deems just.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE GROUNDS OF APPEAL</BOLD> are as follows:</P>
<P>1. The learned Trial Judge erred at law in failing to properly instruct the jury regarding the law of causation.</P>
<P>2. The learned Trial Judge erred at law by giving a charge to the jury that deprived the plaintiff of a fair trial.</P>
<P>3. The learned Trial Judge unfairly and unevenly commented upon the evidence and the credibility of the plaintiff when the credibility of the plaintiff was in dispute and thereby tainted the jury's impression of the plaintiff.</P>
<P>5. The errors of the learned Trial Judge, collectively or individually, resulted in a substantial wrong or a miscarriage of justice that can only be remedied though setting aside the jury's verdict and ordering a new trial.</P>
<P>6. Such further and other grounds as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE BASIS OF THE APPELLATE COURT'S JURISDICTION IS:</BOLD></P>
<P>1. The judgment is a final order of a judge of the Superior Court of Justice;</P>
<P>2. Section 6(1)(b) and 19(1.2)(a) of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990 c C. 43, as amended;</P>
<P>3. Rule 61 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, R.R.O. 1990, Reg 194, as amended; and</P>
<P>4. Leave to appeal is not required.</P>
