<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">Part I&mdash;Nature of Appeal</TI>
<P>1. The charge to the jury is a central feature in any jury trial. In the context of our adversarial process, its strength lies in its objectivity. In an otherwise partisan atmosphere, the jury is entitled to look to the charge to guide it safely through its deliberations and assist it in arriving at a true verdict according to law.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Baltovich</SOC><CITE>2004 CarswellOnt 5013</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paragraph 115; Appellant's Brief of Authorities, Tab 1</P1></P>
<P>2. The plaintiff appeals from the judgment of the Honourable Mr. Justice F. Myers, dated November 18, 2016, made at Toronto, and entered in accordance with a jury verdict. The jury had been tasked with determining Alan Mandel's entitlement to damages arising from a July 4, 2009 motor vehicle accident (&ldquo;Accident&rdquo;). Alan was a passenger in his wife's stopped vehicle when it was struck from behind by the respondents' vehicle.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 222, lines 29&ndash;32 and page 223, lines 1&ndash;16, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, pages 89 and 90</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Justice Myers' charge was partisan and it misdirected the jury as to the test to be applied by it to determine temporal causation.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">Part II&mdash;Overview</TI>
<P>3. Alan Mandel (&ldquo;Alan&rdquo;) had never experienced shoulder pain before the Accident.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. P. Forman, Alan's family doctor testified that he had no notes or recollection of Alan complaining of shoulder pain, jaw or back pain, during the five years that he treated Alan prior to the Accident: page 46, lines 1&ndash;32, page 64, lines 8&ndash;32 and page 65, lines 1&ndash;20, Appeal Book, Tab 7 A, pages 41, 43 and 44</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> From the date of the Accident onwards, Alan experienced significant bilateral shoulder pain, which necessitated painful and time-consuming treatments, and ultimately bilateral shoulder surgery. Although a former supervisor described him as a reliable, productive, enthusiastic person who &ldquo;<EM>loved his job, loved what he was doing</EM>,&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>John Kelly, in-ch, page 349, lines 21&ndash;30, Appeal Book, Tab 7 C, page 114</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> he never regained his ability to work. A devoted father and husband, he remained unable to resume his usual social activities or coach baseball. One of the respondents' medical experts described Alan as &ldquo;straightforward.&rdquo; Another acknowledged that he had no reason to doubt Alan's assertion that he suffered from &ldquo;debilitating&rdquo; pain. Despite an admission of liability and compelling evidence that Alan suffered very serious and permanent physical and psychological impairments, including documented evidence of shoulder complaints within ten days of the Accident, which lead to shoulder surgery, following a thirteen day trial, the jury awarded Alan only $3,000.00 for pain and suffering, and nothing for past or future lost income, future care expenses or housekeeping services.</P>
<P>4. The overriding consideration of the Court is the appearance and preservation of the integrity and fairness of the judicial process. Towards that end, jurors must receive a balanced, impartial charge and proper instructions as to the application of the relevant law in order to reach a fair and proper verdict. Alan asserts that the jury verdict was the result of an inadequate, confusing, and biased jury charge, and respectfully requests that this Court set it aside and substitute its assessment of his damages or, in the alternative, order a new trial.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">Part III&mdash;Facts</TI>
<P>5. The trial of this action was heard by a jury in the City of Toronto in September of 2016, before the Honourable Mr. Justice F. Myers. The action arose from a motor vehicle accident on July 4, 2009. Liability for the Accident was admitted prior to trial: The jury was asked to determine the extent of Alan's damages.</P>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>Alan Mandel's Background</TI>
<P>6. Alan Mandel, born [date omitted]<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 183, lines 8-9, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 71</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, was 52 years old at trial. He is a High school graduate, and married father of three surviving children.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 183, lines 12&ndash;32 and page 184, lines 1&ndash;9, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 72</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>7. From 1987 to January of 2005 (roughly 18 years), Alan worked as general office staff at the Labours International Union of North America, Local 506 (LIUNA) and earned $40,464.00 per annum plus benefits.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 185, lines 9&ndash;32, page 186, lines 1&ndash;31, and page 189, lines 7&ndash;12; Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, pages 74 and 75</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Alan took a leave of absence at LIUNA from May of 2003 to March 2004 (five to six years pre-Accident) due to depression and panic attacks.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 189, lines 13&ndash;29, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 75</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> After he was laid off from LIUNA in 2005, he received regular Employment Insurance benefits for approximately two months<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 191, lines 13&ndash;29 and page 192 lines 1&ndash;3, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, pages 76 and 77</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> while he learned computerized accounting software at Townsend College.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 192, lines 22&ndash;32, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 77</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> From January 30, 2006 until he resigned on November 2, 2007 (approximately 18 months), Alan worked as a debt collector for Allied International Credit.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 193, lines 1&ndash;32 and page 194 lines 1&ndash;31, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, pages 78 and 79</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He was off work from AIC from November 6, 2006 to August 14, 2007, due to severe sinus infections, which ultimately required surgery in July of 2007.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 197, lines 1&ndash;32, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 80</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> On the Monday after he resigned from Allied (November 5, 2007), Alan began working at Livingston International<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 198, lines 16&ndash;30, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 81</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> as a claims adjudicator, inspecting damage to cars transported by train and earned $35,100.00 per annum.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 198, lines 31, page 199, lines 1&ndash;25, and page 201, lines 1&ndash;10 Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, pages 81, 82 and 83</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He was laid off in May 2009 and again received El benefits.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 201, lines 11&ndash;23, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 83</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He was receiving El and looking for employment when the Accident occurred.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 204, lines 6&ndash;32, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 84</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> [Alan's earnings as reported to Revenue Canada from 2004 to 2015 are set out at Schedule C.]</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>The Car Accident</TI>
<P>8. At the time of the Accident, Alan was a front seat-belted passenger in an Uplander minivan being driven by his wife when their vehicle was rear-ended by the respondents' Dodge Nitro.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 224, lines 1&ndash;11, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 91</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The damage to the Mandel vehicle cost $1,401.42 to repair.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 228, lines 5&ndash;13, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 92</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The respondents never disclosed the extent of the damage to their Nitro.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>Alan Mandel's Pre-accident Health</TI>
<P>9. Alan's extensive pre and post-Accident health records were admitted into evidence at trial, and his family doctor, Dr. P. Forman testified. As noted above, although Alan had had some pre- Accident anxiety and depression in around 2003 to 2004 and serious sinus infections which eventually required surgery in July of 2007, there was no evidence that he had ever reported neck, back or shoulder pain or impairments in the five years prior to the 2009 Accident.</P>
<P>10. Even the defence experts, Dr. M. Ford (orthopaedic surgeon) and Dr. R. Zabieliauskas (physiatrist) acknowledged that there was <BOLD>no</BOLD> evidence that Alan ever had neck, back, or shoulder problems prior to the car accident.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Michael Ford, in-ch, page 1107, lines 4&ndash;18, Appeal Book, Tab 7 M, page 181 and Dr. Zabieliaukas, cr-ex, page 952, lines 15&ndash;19, Appeal Book, Tab 7 K, page 176</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>The Causation Evidence</TI>
<P>11. Alan testified at trial that within minutes of the Accident, he experienced a headache and soreness in his neck and shoulders,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 228, lines 17&ndash;30, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 92</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> which increased over the course of the evening.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 229, lines 1&ndash;9, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 93</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Alan saw his family doctor, Dr. P. Forman four days post-Accident. Dr. Forman's clinical note for that visit recorded complaints of right knee pain from a pre-Accident baseball injury and Accident related neck and upper back pain, but did not make any mention of any shoulder problems.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit Book, Tab 1, page 98; Appeal Book, Tab 8 A, page 210</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Having said this, it was apparent at trial that Dr. Forman's notes were clearly incomplete and in some cases entire patient encounters were missing from the chart.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Paul Forman, in-ch, page 75, lines 25&ndash;32, and page 76 lines 1&ndash;14 and cr-ex, page 126, lines 3&ndash;32 and page 127, lines 3&ndash;22, Appeal Book, Tab 7 A, pages 49, 50, 69 and 70</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>12. The first documented record of Alan complaining about his shoulders post-Accident is a note by a physician who was counselling Alan with respect to weight loss, Dr. A. Woodrow, at ten days post-Accident<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Exhibit Book, Tab 1, page 403, Appeal Book, Tab 8 B, page 211</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>13. A detailed chronology of Alan's post-Accident treatment and recorded complaints is attached to this factum at Schedule &ldquo;D&rdquo;. It will be seen that after the visit with Dr. Woodrow, Alan consistently reported ongoing shoulder, neck and back pain and impairments. Ultimately, Dr. R. Richards, a senior orthopaedic surgeon at Sunnybrook Health Sciences Centre, performed decompression surgery on both of Alan's shoulders, the right on February 10, 2012 and the left on May 11, 2012.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Robin Richards, in-ch, page 649, lines 10&ndash;32, page 650, lines 1&ndash;12, and page 653, lines 1&ndash;16, Appeal Book, Tab 7G, pages 141, 142 and 143</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>The Expert Opinion re Causation</TI>
<P>14. On September 1, 2011 Dr. M. Kleinman, physiatrist,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Recognized by the Court as an expert for the purpose of giving opinion evidence in the field of physical medicine and rehabilitation and the diagnosis and treatment of chronic pain: page 585, lines 16&ndash;30</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> assessed Alan at the request of his lawyer. Dr. Kleinman testified at trial that, on examination, Alan had restrictions regarding his ability to lift, bend and complete overhead activities due to his neck, back and shoulder issues, that those restrictions rendered him unemployable,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Max Kleinman, in-ch, page 600, lines 30&ndash;32 and page 601, lines 1&ndash;24, Appeal Book, Tab 8 F, pages 128 and 29</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and that they were directly related to the Accident.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Max Kleinman, in-ch, page 602, lines 10&ndash;23, Appeal Book, Tab 8 F, page 130</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Regarding the issue of the modest property damage, Dr. Kleinman testified that &ldquo;<EM>the medical literature supports the fact that there is no direct correlation between the injuries sustained and the amount of [property] damage</EM>.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Max Kleinman, in-ch, page 602, lines 24&ndash;32 and page 603, lines 1-2, Appeal Book, Tab 8 F, page 130</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>15. On November 23, 2011 Alan was examined by Dr. N. Westreich, psychiatrist, also at the request of his counsel.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Neal Westreich, in-ch, page 499, lines 2&ndash;5, Appeal Book, Tab 8 E, page 119</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Westreich was qualified at trial as an expert in the field of forensic psychiatry and in particular with respect to somatic symptom disorders.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Neal Westreich, in-ch, page 498, lines 5&ndash;14, Appeal Book, Tab 8 F, page 118</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Westreich diagnosed Alan as suffering from a Pain Disorder, associated with both psychological and general medical conditions<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Neal Westreich, in-ch, page 514, lines 26&ndash;30, Appeal Book, Tab 8 F, page 120</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> as a result of the Accident.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Neal Westreich, in-ch, page 520, lines 4&ndash;14, Appeal Book, Tab 8 F, page 121</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. Dr. R. Richards testified at trial that Alan had permanently reduced abilities to engage in activities involving heavy lifting, overhead activity, or any repetitive or forceful use of his arms,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Robin Richards, in-ch, page 658, lines 14&ndash;32 and page 659, line 1, Appeal Book, Tab 8 G, page 145</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> which limited his occupational, recreational, and household activities, and negatively impacted his ability to be competitive in the workplace.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Robin Richards, in-ch, page 659, lines 11&ndash;30, Appeal Book, Tab 8 F, page 146</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Those limitations included playing baseball, shovelling snow, raking, vacuuming, changing light bulbs, lifting heavy groceries and any other similar daily activities.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Robin Richards, in-ch, page 660, lines 5&ndash;22, Appeal Book, Tab 8 F, page 147</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> At trial, when asked whether Alan's shoulder problems were caused by the Accident, Dr. Richards testified, &ldquo;<EM>well, as far as I'm concerned, for sure they were caused by the accident. I mean, he didn't have problems before he had the accident and within a short period of time he developed symptoms that went on and on and on...the imaging studies would also provide corroborative evidence of that being the case</EM>.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Robin Richards, in-ch, page 662, lines 10&ndash;20, Appeal Book, Tab 7 G, page 148</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>17. On October 2, 2012 Dr. M. Ford, orthopedic surgeon,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>The Court qualified Dr. Ford to provide opinion evidence in areas of orthopedic surgery with a sub-speciality in spinal orthopedic surgery: Dr. Michael Ford, in-ch, page 1075, lines 23&ndash;32, and page 1076, line 1 Appeal Book, Tab 7 M, page 173</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> assessed Alan at the request of the respondents.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Michael Ford, in-ch, page 1075, lines 4&ndash;9, Appeal Book, Tab 7 M, page 184</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Ford testified at trial that he was not aware of any evidence that Alan had reported any back, neck or shoulder complaints in the four years prior to the Accident.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Michael Ford, in-ch, page 1107, lines 4&ndash;18, Appeal Book, Tab 7 M, page 181</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Ford accepted that Alan's neck and back pain were Accident related.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Michael Ford, in-ch, page 1126, lines 18&ndash;30, Appeal Book, Tab 7 M, page 183</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He did not accept causation with respect to the shoulder problems because there was no contemporaneous record documenting the immediate onset of shoulder complaints<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Michael Ford, in-ch, page 1090, lines 4&ndash;32 and page 1091, lines 1&ndash;3, Appeal Book, Tab 7 M, page 185</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He assumed that Dr. Forman's clinical notes were a complete record of Alan's contemporaneous complaints.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Michael Ford, cr-ex, page 1113, lines 10&ndash;13, Appeal Book, Tab 7 M, page 182</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>18. On October 11, 2012 Dr. R. Zabieliauskas, physiatrist, assessed Alan at the request of the respondents.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Raymond J. Zabieliauskas, in-ch, page 915, lines 3&ndash;5, Appeal Book, Tab 7 K, page 170</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Zabieliauskas described Dr. Richards as an &ldquo;excellent&rdquo; surgeon.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Raymond J. Zabieliauskas, in-ch, page 935, lines 3&ndash;5, Appeal Book, Tab 7 K, page 172</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> During Dr. Zabieliauskas' assessment, Alan reported having 9/10 jaw pain, 9/10 headaches and 9/10 bilateral shoulder pain.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Raymond J. Zabieliauskas, in-ch, page 937, lines 4&ndash;18, Appeal Book, Tab 7 K, page 173</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Zabieliauskas described Alan as &ldquo;affable&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Raymond J. Zabieliauskas, cr-ex, page 947, lines 3&ndash;8, Appeal Book, Tab 7 K, page 174</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and &ldquo;sincere&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Raymond J. Zabieliauskas, cr-ex, page 947, lines 24-25, Appeal Book, Tab 7 K, page 174</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> When asked if he believed that Alan had debilitating pain, Dr. Zabieliauskas said that he had &ldquo;no reason to doubt him.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Raymond J. Zabieliauskas, cr-ex, page 947, lines 26&ndash;32 and page 948, lines 1&ndash;3, Appeal Book, Tab 7 M, page 174</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Zabieliauskas also testified that the dollar damage to a vehicle was not necessarily an absolute indicator of the severity of an accident<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Raymond J. Zabieliauskas, cr-ex, page 951, lines 19&ndash;26, Appeal Book, Tab 7 M, page 175</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and acknowledged that if the jury accepted Alan's evidence that he experienced shoulder pain on the day of the Accident, it was more likely than not that that the Accident caused his shoulder problems.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Raymond J. Zabieliauskas, cr-ex, page 974, lines 6&ndash;22, Appeal Book, Tab 7 M, page 177</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Zabieliausksas testified that he believed that accident related complaints generally developed within 24 to 72 hours of an accident and that he would &ldquo;<EM>have a hard time to perform the temporal link between voiced complaints</EM> [from a motor vehicle accident] <EM>beyond four days as being related to an accident</EM>,&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Raymond J. Zabieliauskas, cr-ex, page 932, lines 5&ndash;20, Appeal Book, Tab 7 M, page 171</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Zabieliauskas conceded that shoulder injuries incurred by bracing for car accidents are very common.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Raymond J. Zabieliauskas, cr-ex, page 974, line 23&ndash;32 and page 975, lines 1&ndash;6, Appeal Book, Tab 7 M, page 177</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>19. On July 31, 2013 Dr. Westreich reassessed Alan.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. N. Westreich, in-ch, page 520, lines 14-15, Appeal Book, Tab 7 E, page 121</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He testified at trial that as of that assessment, Alan's usage of medication had increased significantly over time, despite having received therapy and injections for pain.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. N. Westreich, in-ch, page 524, lines 1&ndash;24, Appeal Book, Tab 7 E, page 122</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Westreich again diagnosed Alan as having a somatic symptom disorder with predominant pain, persistent, severe<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. N. Westreich, in-ch, page 531, lines 21&ndash;26, Appeal Book, Tab 7 E, page 124</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> due to the Accident. Dr. Westreich testified that Alan's &ldquo;<EM>life was totally consumed with his pain and with his treatment</EM>&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. N. Westreich, in-ch, page 530, lines 18&ndash;30, Appeal Book, Tab 7 E, page 123</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and concluded that Alan's condition was &ldquo;<EM>going to the stay the same or maybe get worse</EM>.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. N. Westreich, in-ch, page 534, lines 1&ndash;13, Appeal Book, Tab 7 E, page 125</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Westreich described Alan as experiencing chronic unremitting pain in multiple anatomical sites.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. N. Westreich, in-ch, page 534, lines 20&ndash;23, Appeal Book, Tab 7 E, page 125</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Westreich also testified that he believed that because of his Accident related impairments, Alan would not be able to return to work.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. N. Westreich, in-ch, page 534, line 32 and page 535, lines 1&ndash;7, Appeal Book, Tab 7 E, pages 125 and 126</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>20. On August 6, 2013 Alan was assessed by Dr. D. A. Young, psychologist,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Young was qualified as an expert witness for the purpose of giving opinion evidence concerning the field of psychology: Dr. D. A. Young, in-ch, page 1005, lines 19&ndash;23, Appeal Book, Tab 7 L, page 178</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> at the request of the respondents. Dr. Young also testified at trial that he found Alan to be &ldquo;straightforward&rdquo; and he acknowledged that Alan was suffering from what appeared to be legitimate pain.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Donald A. Young, in-ch, page 1043, lines 21&ndash;32, Appeal Book, Tab 7 L, page 179</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>21. On August 20, 2013 Dr. Kleinman reassessed Alan.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Max Kleinman, in-ch, page 603, lines 17&ndash;19, Appeal Book, Tab 7 F, page 131</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Kleinman testified that during that reassessment Alan complained of pain in the same areas at pretty much the same intensity.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Max Kleinman, in-ch, page 603, lines 20&ndash;32 and page 604, lines 1&ndash;29, Appeal Book, Tab 7 F, page 131</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Alan, however, had a 12.5 cm surgical scar on his right arm and a 9 cm surgical scar on his left arm.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Max Kleinman, in-ch, page 605, lines 10&ndash;15, Appeal Book, Tab 7 F, page 133</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Kleinman testified that Alan continued to have serious and permanent ongoing difficulties completing his general activities of daily living, including social and recreational activities.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Max Kleinman, in-ch, page 606, lines 28&ndash;32 and page 607, lines 1&ndash;4, Appeal Book, Tab 7 F, page 134</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Kleinman also concluded that Alan was precluded from returning to work and completing the heavier aspects of his household activities as a result of the Accident, and that the likelihood of functional improvement to any significant degree was &ldquo;essentially non-existent.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Max Kleinman, in-ch, page 607, lines 5&ndash;32 and page 608, lines 1&ndash;20, Appeal Book, Tab 7 F, page 135</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>Impact of Accident on Alan Mandel</TI>
<P>22. At the time of the trial, Alan continued to experience increasing symptoms, including headaches, migraines, an inability to concentrate, shoulder pain, neck pain, back pain, facial pain, leg pain, hand pain and feet pain.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 282, lines 1&ndash;31 and page 283, lines 26&ndash;32, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, pages 108 and 109</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>23. Prior to the accident, Alan was a coach for the Richmond Hill Phoenix Baseball club and played baseball and road hockey with friends.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 219, lines 30&ndash;32; and page 220, lines 1&ndash;30, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, pages 86 and 87</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> At the time of trial, Alan remained unable to coach or play baseball,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 284, lines 8&ndash;18, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 110</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> play with or take his children to sporting events, sit for any prolonged period of time, or tolerate crowds and loud noises.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 284, lines 19&ndash;32, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 110</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>24. Prior to the Accident, Alan was responsible for yard maintenance, snow shovelling, and cooking.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 221, lines 13&ndash;32, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 88</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> At the time of trial, Alan remained unable to cook,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 285, lines 9&ndash;11, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 111</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> help with general housekeeping chores, including laundry,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 285, lines 20&ndash;27, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 112</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> or undertake any home maintenance activities, including yard work and shovelling snow.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 286, lines 14&ndash;30, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 112</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> His ability to grocery shop and socialize remained limited to only his &ldquo;good days.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 286, lines 11&ndash;13, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 112</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> <FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 287, lines 12&ndash;19, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 113</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He had remained unable to work or look for work since the Accident, due to unremitting chronic pain.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 208, lines 4&ndash;27, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 85</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> <FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 281, lines 18&ndash;24, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 106</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>25. At the time of trial, Alan continued to rely upon morphine for the control of severe pain, 300 mg of Gabapentin three times per day for nerve pain, 60 mg per day of Cymbalta, an antidepressant, to his control pain and for his depression, and 10 mg of Baclofen, a muscle relaxant, three times' a day.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Paul Forman, in-ch, page 107, lines 6&ndash;29, Appeal Book, Tab 7 A, page 68</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He was also receiving painful nerve block injections once per week.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 244, lines 13&ndash;27, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 104</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>26. The jury also heard from Alan's wife, Jaimi, who testified that since the Accident, Alan had been extremely irritable, angry, short tempered, impatient, and intolerant.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Jaimi Mandel, in-ch, page 686, lines 17&ndash;24, Appeal Book, Tab 7 H, page 149</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> She also testified that on a &ldquo;bad day&rdquo; Alan's functionality was &ldquo;non-existent&rdquo;: he was unable to get out of bed, needed assistance to use the washroom, and was unable to interact with her or with their children.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Jaimi Mandel, in-ch, page 687, lines 13&ndash;17, Appeal Book, Tab 7 H, page 150</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> On a &ldquo;good day&rdquo;, Alan was able to drive himself or their children short distances.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Jaimi Mandel, in-ch, page 687, lines 18&ndash;25, Appeal Book, Tab 7 H, page 150</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Jaimi also said that since the accident, &ldquo;<EM>Alan is less communicative, less intimate, less spontaneous, less romantic...he used to have a really good sense of humour and we don't laugh anymore</EM>.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Jaimi Mandel, in-ch, page 694, lines 26&ndash;31, Appeal Book, Tab 7 H, page 151</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Based on her observations of Alan, Alan's problems, in totality, appeared to be increasing over time.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Jaimi Mandel, in-ch, page 695, lines 1&ndash;4, Appeal Book, Tab 7 H, page 152</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>E.</N><TI>Economic Loss / Future Care Costs Evidence</TI>
<P>27. On November 25, 2015 Bonnie Koreen, occupational therapist,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Ms. Koreen was qualified by the Court to give expert evidence with respect to life care planning and future care costs: Bonnie Koreen, in-ch, page 717, lines 14&ndash;24, Appeal Book, Tab 7 I, page 153</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> assessed Alan at his home.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Bonnie Koreen, in-ch, page 719, lines 15&ndash;19, Appeal Book, Tab 7 I, page 154</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> At trial, Ms. Koreen testified that she had assessed Alan's functional ability and tolerance and found that he had &ldquo;major&rdquo; restrictions in all movements of his neck and back.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Bonnie Koreen, in-ch, page 726, lines 12&ndash;32 and page 727, lines 1-2, Appeal Book, Tab 7 I, pages 155 and 166</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Ms. Koreen recommended that Alan continue to receive OHIP funded medical services, as well as participate in a multidisciplinary program to address his chronic pain complaints.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Bonnie Koreen, in-ch, page 733, lines 2&ndash;32, Appeal Book, Tab 7 I, page 157</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> She also recommended an additional 25 hours of occupational therapy intervention to address any future functional needs,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Bonnie Koreen, in-ch, page 735, lines 6&ndash;10, Appeal Book, Tab 7 I, page 158</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> assistance from a personal trainer twice per year,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Bonnie Koreen, in-ch, page 735, lines 27&ndash;32 and page 736, lines 1&ndash;5, Appeal Book, Tab 7 I, pages 158 and 159</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> ongoing massage therapy and chiropractic treatment,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Bonnie Koreen, in-ch, page 736, lines 6&ndash;17, Appeal Book, Tab 7 I, page 159</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the provision of four hours per week of homemaking services until age 80,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Bonnie Koreen, in-ch, page 737, lines 24&ndash;32 and page 738, lines 1&ndash;30, Appeal Book, Tab 7 I, pages 160 and 161</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> a vocational assessment and vocational counselling.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Bonnie Koreen, in-ch, page 742, lines 1&ndash;9, Appeal Book, Tab 7 I, page 162</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Ms. Koreen prepared tables setting out the cost of the recommended services which was made available to the jury.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Trial Exhibit Tab 35, page 2642, Appeal Book, Tab 8 D, page 213</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The respondents did not adduce any expert opinion evidence with respect to Alan's needs.</P>
<P>28. In 2010 Alan received a job offer from Nortown Plumbing<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>As of the date of the trial, Nortown Plumbing is not in business; Alan Mandel, in-ch page 281, lines 25&ndash;28, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 106</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (his mother-in-law's companion's business) to work in a warehouse.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 280, lines 16&ndash;30, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 107</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Alan declined the job offer because his shoulder pain &ldquo;<EM>wouldn't allow [him] to do that type of work</EM>.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 281, lines 2&ndash;8, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 106</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The job paid approximately $42,000.00.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 281, lines 12&ndash;15, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 106</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>29. Effective March 2014, Alan was found to be eligible to receive Canada Pension Plan disability pension benefits.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Alan Mandel, in-ch, page 275, lines 13&ndash;20, Appeal Book, Tab 7 B, page 105</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>30. Dr. E. Katz, economist, was qualified by the Court to give expert opinion evidence with respect to the quantification of Alan's past and future income loss and the present value of Alan's future healthcare claims.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Eliakim Katz, in-ch, page 796, lines 10&ndash;27, Appeal Book, Tab 7 J, page 163</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Statistically, in 2010 Alan would have likely earned, but for the Accident, $23,872.00.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Eliakim Katz, in-ch, page 812, lines 7&ndash;19, Appeal Book, Tab 7 J, page 164</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Katz also testified that Alan's likely earnings would have been $27,225.00 in 2011,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Eliakim Katz, in-ch, page 812, lines 20&ndash;28, Appeal Book, Tab 7 J, page 164</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> $28,700.00 in 2012, $29,572.00 in 2013, $30,376.00 in 2014 and $33,528.00 in 2015.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Eliakim Katz, in-ch, page 813, lines 3&ndash;14, Appeal Book, Tab 7 J, page 165</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Katz also considered a second scenario in which, but for the Accident, Alan would have earned the average income of a fulltime customer service representative in Toronto, in which case, as of 2016, Alan would have been earning $44,504.00 per annum.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Eliakim Katz, in-ch, page 813, lines 26&ndash;32 and page 814, lines 1&ndash;9, Appeal Book, Tab 7 J, pages 165 and 166</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Katz estimated the present value of Alan's probable future loss of income to age 68, taking into account appropriate discounts, including mandated discount rates, ranged from $364,588.00 to $457,203.00.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Eliakim Katz, in-ch, page 833, lines 14&ndash;27, Appeal Book, Tab 7 J, page 167</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Dr. Katz testified that the present value of the medication, assistive devices, and housekeeping / home maintenance services recommended by Ms. Koreen totalled $447,680.00.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dr. Eliakim Katz, in-ch, page 836, lines 10&ndash;32 and page 837, lines 1&ndash;19, Appeal Book, Tab 7 J, pages 168 and 169</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>F.</N><TI>Surveillance</TI>
<P>31. The jury was shown surveillance of Alan. A chart setting out the dates and times that surveillance was conducted at the request of the respondents is at Schedule &ldquo;E.&rdquo; Out of the total 137 hours and 27 minutes of surveillance that was conducted, Alan was observed for 11 hours and 49 minutes, and during that time, he was videotaped for a total of 2 hours and 5 minutes. The video footage did not show Alan performing any activities that he had not already admitted to being able to do on one of his &ldquo;good days&rdquo;, prior to the surveillance being shown.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>G.</N><TI>Closing, Charge and Jury Verdict</TI>
<P>32. During the appellant's closing submission, the jury was invited to find that Alan had sustained a chronic pain (somatic symptom disorder) as a result of the Accident.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Plaintiff's closing submissions, page 80, lines 11-12, Appeal Book, Tab 7 O, page 198</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The jury was asked by the appellant to award him $150,000.00 to $160,000.00 for his pain and suffering, $100,000.00 for past loss income, $420,000.00 for future lost income, $126,685.00 for lost housekeeping services, and $321,895.00 for future health care expenses.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Plaintiff's closing submissions, page 90, lines 17&ndash;27, page 93, lines 25&ndash;28, page 94, lines 24&ndash;30 and page 98, lines 17&ndash;26 Appeal Book, Tab 7 O, pages 199, 200, 201 and 202</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>33. Over the objection of the appellant's counsel,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Submissions on the Charge, page 1196, lines 4&ndash;32, page 1197, page 1198 and page 1199, lines 1&ndash;26; Appeal Book, Tab 7 N, pages 186 and 187, 188 and 189</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> during his charge, Justice Myers provided obscure instructions to the jury on the critical issue of the temporal connection between the Accident and Alan's shoulder issues:
<QUOTE><P>In assessing causation, it's important to avoid the logical fallacy of automatically assuming a causal connection between two events just because one closely follows the other in time. We have all heard about cases where children have become very ill shortly after receiving vaccinations, yet the science is clear that the vaccines often do not cause illness. People naturally want to ascribe cause and the most recent event is the most natural conclusion. However, the simple fact that something came first and something else came after does not automatically or necessarily prove causation.</P>
<P>In a vaccine case, a former judge of this court wrote that, &ldquo;Statistically within any large group of population, the chances of a number of illnesses developing within three days of virtually any observable event are great.&rdquo;</P>
<P>Mr. Mandel put his shoes on in the morning before his motor vehicle accident. No one would say that just because he started to feel pain shortly after putting on his shoes that the shoes caused the pain. You have to look at all the evidence and see if he's proven that but for the motor vehicle accident he would not have incurred his losses.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Charge to the jury, page 1278, lines 1&ndash;27 Appeal Book, Tab 7 P, page 206</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>34. During pre-charge submissions, the appellant's trial counsel suggested that the jury simply be advised that a temporal connection between an accident and the development of pain was not determinative by itself that the accident had caused the pain, but was, nonetheless, a relevant factor for the jury to consider.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Submissions on the Charge, page 1196, lines 4&ndash;32, Appeal Book, Tab 7 N, page 186</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>35. Contrary to the tenet that a judge's viewpoint must not appear to unfairly influence the jury, the charge improperly (and over the objection of the appellant's counsel<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Submissions on the Charge, page 1207, lines 2&ndash;32, page 1208, page 1209, page 1210, page 1211, page 1212, page 1213, and page 1214, lines 1&ndash;10, Appeal Book, Tab 7 N, pages 190, 191, 192, 193, 194, 195, 196 and 197</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>) organized the evidence to provide an analysis that effectively encouraged the jury to conclude that Alan's ongoing problems were unrelated to the Accident, even though <BOLD>no</BOLD> other explanation for them was offered at trial:
<QUOTE><P>Many issues in this case come down to credibility i.e. whose testimony do you accept? In assessing the credibility and reliability of testimony, you might want to consider the following questions:</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>5. Was the witness honest and forthright? You heard one example of a witness's testimony being impeached with evidence of a prior inconsistent statement. You may recall that Mr. Mandel testified that he saw the car coming at them in the passenger's side mirror. On his out of court examination for discovery, in which he was under oath, he swore that he &lsquo;looked up&rsquo; at the driver's rear view mirror when he saw Ms. Fakhim's vehicle coming. He is recorded as having told several doctors this too. He agreed in court that sitting in the passenger's seat, he would not likely have been able to see Ms. Fakhim's car coming in the driver's rearmview mirror. If he did not see the car coming, how could he have braced? His testimony changed at trial from looking up at the rear view mirror to looking at the side mirror. When confronted with the inconsistency in a sworn testimony, he said that this was an example of the problem he was having fumbling for words due to his injury. Does that strike you as a reasonable, credible explanation exercising your common sense? Does fumbling between the words rear view and side view explain why he said that he was looking up at the mirror? Does it explain why he wrote &lsquo;I was looking in the rear view mirror&rsquo; in the OCF 3 benefits claim form as early as July 24, 2009 that's Exhibit 3? You should assess the difference between Mr. Mandel's testimony on examination for discovery, and at trial, and come to your own conclusion as to whether if affects your view of the credibility of his testimony. It is open to you to find that he was correct at trial, that he made a simple mistake, he lied, or anything in between.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Charge to the jury, pages 1247, lines 25&ndash;30 and Page 1248, lines 1&ndash;25 Appeal Book, Tab 7 P, pages 203 and 204</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>7. Does a witness show any tendency to exaggerate? ...You might also consider whether Mr. Mandel was exaggerating his pain? Dr. Young says that his test results showed that Mr. Mandel exaggerates the physical pains he suffers. Dr. Ford said that he reported back pain using the Waddell test, model test, that are designed to determine if there's a non-organic component to a person's pain.</P>
<P>You saw Mr. Mandel for more than two weeks. He stood up once every so often and walked around at the back of the courtroom. You saw him under pressure in the witness stand several times as his testimony was interrupted by others. He says that in a week he has one or two good days, one or two bad days where he must stay in bed and can only sit up to watch TV, and the rest are really bad days when he can only get out of bed to go to the washroom with help. He has had no nerve blocks since the week before the trial started. Did you see someone suffering 9 out of 10 pain, with 10 being the worst pain imaginable? Did you see corroboration of his description of his good, bad, and really bad days? He said he goes right to bed at night and that he had to take hydromorphone on the first weekend during the trial. You saw the surveillance video, all but one of which was taken at least a week after Mr. Mandel had his most recent nerve block. Was it consistent with how Mr. Mandel described his pain and his functional limitations?<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Charge to the jury, page 1250, lines 15&ndash;25; Appeal Book, Tab 7 P, page 205</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>Here you know that there was a minor collision. You know the damage to the vehicles. You will have the repair details with you in the jury room. You have Mr. Mandel's work history and his health history. You know the details of his extensive treatments he has endured over the past seven years. Did he suffer physical disabilities before the MVA? Are his reports of depression, disc pain, arthritis in his neck, heartburn, and sinus pain, all of which kept him from work for varying periods of time before the MVA relevant to the disabilities from which he now suffers? Did he have psychological issues with his father's death, overreaction to pain, or problems with working before the MVA? Is the fact that Dr. Forman counselled Mr. Mandel for 22 minutes about his mother's cancer diagnosis on the same day that Mr. Mandel first reported his problems relevant to a psychological disability if you accept that he has one? Was he looking at the side view mirror before the accident? Did he know that a car was coming? If so, did he brace with his arms in front of him as he testified? Did he stiffen up while sitting erect as he told doctors?<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Charge to the Jury, page 1279, lines 11&ndash;32 and page 1280, lines 1&ndash;3; Appeal Book, Tab 7 P, paged 207 and 208</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>36. The jury was provided with a copy of the jury charge to reference during its deliberations.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Charge to the Jury, page 1304, lines 3&ndash;5; Appeal Book, Tab 7 P, page 209</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>37. The jury ultimately awarded Alan $3,000.00 for non-pecuniary general damages and nothing else.</P>
<P>38. Contrary to section 267.5(15) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> R.S.O. 1990 c.I8, as amended, Justice Myers declined to determine whether Alan sustained the required &ldquo;threshold&rdquo; impairments to claim entitlement to non-pecuniary damages as per section 267.5(5) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, stating:
<QUOTE><P>10 If a judge can find facts that are inconsistent with the jury's findings and that have legal effect, what justification is there to summon people away from their lives to compel them to attend court? I am already being paid to do the same job anyway.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>18 In my view, this is precisely the case where the doctrine of mootness requires full application. If the decision that I am called upon to make risks undermining the jury's clear findings and my decision has no effect in any event because plaintiff will receive no damages as a result of the jury's verdict and the statutory deductible, then not only is there no purpose in making the threshold decision, but making the decision risks undermining the important and singular function of the jury.</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">Part III&mdash;Issues</TI>
<P>39. The following issues are raised by this appeal:
<P1>i. Did the trial judge err at law in failing to properly instruct the jury regarding the law of temporal causation?</P1>
<P1>ii. Did the jury charge deprive the plaintiff of a fair trial?</P1>
<P1>iii. Is the $3,000.00 award so inordinately low that appellate intervention is warranted?</P1>
<P1>iv. Did the trial judge err at law in failing to determine the issue of &ldquo;threshold&rdquo; impairment?</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">Part IV&mdash;The law</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>The Standard of Review</TI>
<P>40. An appellate court can and should interfere if a trial judge's charge fails to direct a jury in dealing with the essentials of a case and a substantial wrong or miscarriage is occasioned. Appellate intervention may be warranted if there is shown to be misdirection or non-direction by the trial judge.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Stewart v Speer</SOC><CITE>1953 CarswellOnt 234</CITE><PAGENUM>at 2-3</PAGENUM></CASEREF>, Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 2</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Marcoccia (Litigation Guardian of) v Gill</SOC><CITE>2009 CarswellOnt 2967</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 26, Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 3</P1></P>
<P>41. Appellate intervention with respect to the assessment of damages will more readily be warranted where there has been misdirection or non-direction on the part of the trial judge.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Laufer v Bucklaschuk</SOC><CITE>1999 CarswellMan 565</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 111, Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 4</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>There was serious misdirection in the charge to the jury regarding temporal causation, such that the jury was ill-equipped to serve its important function as trier of fact.</TI>
<P>42. It is incumbent upon a trial judge to distill the applicable law and explain it to the jury in a clear, understandable manner.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Pereira v. Hamilton Township Farmers' Mutual Fire Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2006 CarswellOnt 2279</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at para 70; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 5</P1></P>
<P>43. An injured plaintiff must show on a balance of probabilities that he was injured by the defendant and that his injury would not have occurred but for a defendant's negligence. The &ldquo;but for&rdquo; test must be applied in a robust common sense fashion. There is no need for scientific evidence of the precise contribution the defendant's negligence made to the injury.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Clements v. Clements</SOC><CITE>2012 CarswellBC 1863</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras 8-9; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 6</P1></P>
<P>44. There is no legal principle that holds that if a collision is not severe or violent, or if there is no significant damage to a motor vehicle, the individual seated within that vehicle at the time of the impact cannot have sustained injuries. The authorities clearly establish that, while the lack of vehicle damage may be a relevant consideration, the extent of the injuries suffered by a plaintiff is not to be measured by the severity of the force in a collision or the degree of the vehicle's damage. Rather, the existence and extent of a plaintiff's injuries is to be determined on the basis of the evidentiary record at trial.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gordon v. Palmer</SOC><CITE>1993 CarswellBC 95</CITE><COURTJUR>SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras 4&ndash;6 Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 7</P1></P>
<P>45. <CASEREF><SOC>White v. Stonestreet</SOC></CASEREF> dealt with the reliability of inferences drawn from temporal connections when determining causation. Justice Ehrcke explained it this way:
<QUOTE><P>[74] The inference from a temporal sequence to a causal connection, however, is not always reliable. In fact, this form of reasoning so often results in false conclusions that logicians have given it a Latin name. It is sometimes referred to as the fallacy of <EM>post hoc ergo propter hoc</EM>: &ldquo;after this therefore because of this.&rdquo;</P>
<P>[75] In searching for causes, a temporal connection is sometimes the only thing to go on. But if a mere temporal connection is going to form the basis for a conclusion about the cause of an event, then it is important to examine that temporal connection carefully. Just how close are the events in time? Were there other events happening around the same time, or even closer in time, that would provide an alternate, and more accurate, explanation of the true cause?</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>White v. Stonestreet</SOC><CITE>2006 CarswellBC 1257</CITE><COURTJUR>SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 8</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Madill v. Sithivong</SOC><CITE>2012 CarswellBC 224</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 20; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 9</P1></P>
<P>46. It does not, however, follow that the judicial urging of caution signifies judicial thinking that temporal reasoning is an illegitimate analysis or a branch of logic to be seldom invoked.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Anderson v. Rizzardo</SOC><CITE>2015 CarswellBC 3679</CITE><PARANUM>140</PARANUM></CASEREF>; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 10</P1></P>
<P>47. A temporal connection between an accident and the development of pain is not determinative by itself that the Accident caused the pain, but it is, nonetheless, a relevant factor.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Worobetz v. Fooks</SOC><CITE>2015 CarswellBC 236</CITE><PARANUM>93</PARANUM></CASEREF>; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 11</P1></P>
<P>48. In <CASEREF><SOC>Midgley v. Nguyen</SOC></CASEREF>, which concerned claim for damages as a result of a motor vehicle accident, the British Columbia Supreme Court stated:
<QUOTE><P>[167] Whether a defendant is liable to a plaintiff for an injury is a matter of causation. It is crucial to keep in mind the analytical distinction between determining causation and assessing damages, since different principles govern the two questions.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>[168] The primary test to be applied in determining causation is commonly articulated as the &lsquo;but for&rsquo; test. The plaintiff bears the burden of showing that &lsquo;but for&rsquo; the negligent act or omission of the defendant, the plaintiff's injury would not have occurred.</P>
<P>[169] The &lsquo;but for&rsquo; test need not be determined with scientific precision. Rather, causation is a practical question of fact which can be best answered by ordinary common sense.</P>
<P>[170] A plaintiff need not establish that a defendant's tortious conduct is the sole cause of the injury. A defendant will be fully liable for the hard suffered by a plaintiff, even if other casual factors for which he is not responsible were at play in producing the harm, as long as the plaintiff establishes a substantial connection between the injuries and the defendant's negligence beyond the &lsquo;<EM>de minimus</EM>&rsquo; range.</P>
<P>[171] The court must be cautious when inferring causation from a temporal sequence; that is, from a consideration of pre-accident versus post-accident condition. <BOLD>In cases where causation is asserted primarily on a temporal relationship between the negligent conduct and injury in question, the authorities mandate that a &lsquo;close scrutiny of the evidence is required because the inference from a temporal sequence to a causal connection is not always reliable.&rsquo; However, the authorities recognize that temporal reasoning is not an illegitimate analysis if invoked in the appropriate circumstances</BOLD>. [Emphasis added].</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Midgley v. Nguyen</SOC><CITE>2013 CarswellBC 1029</CITE><COURTJUR>SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 12</P1></P>
<P>49. While an appellate court reviewing a trial judge's charge will not hold the instructions to a jury to a standard of perfection, there should be a focus on whether the jury would have, considering the charge in its entirety, properly understood the law.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Pereira v Hamilton Township Farmer's Mutual Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2006 CarswellOnt 2279</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 51, Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 5</P1></P>
<P>50. The overarching issue in this trial was whether the appellant had proved on a balance of probabilities that his medical conditions (in particular his shoulder issues) were caused by the Accident. The trial judge's charge to the jury regarding temporal causation was, with respect, wrong at law and misleading, in that it involved non-material examples and undermined the appellant's valid assertion that the very close and well-documented temporal connection between the Accident and his shoulder injuries and the complete absence of any other explanation for those injuries, was the critical factor for the jury to consider when determining causation.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>The trial judge cannot usurp or influence the role of the jury.</TI>
<P>51. A jury charge must be even-handed, the instructions fair and balanced. No sides should be taken and no editorial comment should intrude.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Largie</SOC><CITE>2010 CarswellOnt 5801</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 127; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 13</P1></P>
<P>52. In appeals based on errors in the conduct of the trial by pre-judgment of issues and undue interventions, the test is not prejudice but whether the image of impartiality, the absence of which deprives the court of jurisdiction, has been destroyed.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Majcenic v. Natale</SOC><CITE>1967 CarswellOnt 179</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 47; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 14</P1></P>
<P>53. The presumption of judicial impartiality may be rebutted by evidence of a reasonable apprehension of bias. The classic test for reasonable apprehension of bias is that set out by Grandpr&ea; J. in <CASEREF><SOC>Committee for Justice &amp; Liberty v. Canada (National Energy Board)</SOC></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>[T]he apprehension of bias must be a reasonable one, held by reasonable and right-minded persons, applying themselves to the question and obtaining thereon the required information ... [T]hat test is &ldquo;what would an informed person, viewing the matter realistically and practically&mdash;and having thought the matter through&mdash;conclude. Would he think that it is more likely than not that [the judge], whether consciously or unconsciously, would not decide fairly.&rdquo; [my emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Committee for Justice &amp; Liberty v. Canada (National Energy Board)</SOC><CITE>1976 CarswellNat 434</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 40; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 15</P1></P>
<P>54. The trial judge has no right to intervene in such a manner as to constitute possible injustice to either party. When a judge intervenes in the trial to such an extent that he or she projects himself into the arena, the judge, of necessity, adopts a position which is inimical to the interests of one or other of the litigants. Those actions, whether conscious or unconscious, no matter how well intentioned or motivated, creates an atmosphere which violates the principle that &ldquo;justice not only be done, but appear to be done&rdquo;. Intervention amounting to interference in the conduct of a tri al destroys the image of judicial impartiality and deprives the Court of jurisdiction. The right to intervene is one of degree and there cannot be a precise line of demarcation, but if it can be fairly said that it amounted to the usurpation of the function of counsel it is not permissible.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Majcenic v. Natale</SOC></CASEREF>, supra, at Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 14</P1></P>
<P>55. Where the effect of the trial judge's intervention destroys the image of impartiality that the court must maintain, the result is loss of jurisdiction.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Henderson v. Henderson</SOC><CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 11408</CITE><COURTJUR>SCJ</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras 33, 40; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 15</P1></P>
<P>56. In <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Baltovich</SOC></CASEREF> the Court of Appeal stressed the importance of an objective jury charge, albeit in the context of a criminal matter:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>115 The charge to the jury is a central feature in any jury trial. In the context of our adversarial process, its strength lies in its objectivity. In an otherwise partisan atmosphere, the jury is entitled to look to the charge to guide it safely through its deliberations and assist it in arriving at a true verdict according to law.</BOLD></P>
<P>116 Much has been said in recent years about the complexity of jury charges and the need to simplify them. Trial judges face a difficult task in this regard, especially when it comes to explaining complicated issues of law. In <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Jacquard</SOC><YEAR>1997</YEAR><CITE>113 C.C.C. (3d) 1</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 2, Chief Justice Lamer observed that while &ldquo;accused individuals are entitled to properly instructed juries&rdquo;, there is &ldquo;no requirement for perfectly instructed juries&rdquo;. Those words are as true today as they were then. No one expects perfection in a jury charge. Mistakes are bound to occur.</P>
<P><BOLD>117 But not all mistakes are alike. Some can easily be avoided. Failing to provide the jury with a fair and balanced charge is one of them. There is no justification for jury charges that are not even-handed.</BOLD></P>
<P>118 We cannot stress enough the importance of a fair and balanced charge. A charge that meets those requirements is much more likely to withstand appellate review than one that does not: See <EM>Jacquard</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> at para. 56. In practical terms, this may mean the difference between dismissing the appeal, and ordering a new trial with all of its attendant costs and hardships. Our system of justice is already overburdened. We do not need to add to this problem with new trials that could have been avoided. Further, s. 11(d) of the <EM>Charter</EM> provides that every person charged with an offence has the right to a fair trial. This is a fundamental right. Unfair and unbalanced charges undermine this right [<EM>emphasis added</EM>].</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Baltovich</SOC></CASEREF>, supra, Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 1</P1></P>
<P>57. Similarly, in <CASEREF><SOC>Duong v. R</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court of Appeal stressed:
<QUOTE><P>We have in mind that the charge to the jury is the central feature in any jury trial. In the context of our adversarial process, its strength lies in its objectivity. There is no justification for jury charges that are not even&mdash;handed.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Duong v. R</SOC><CITE>2007 CarswellOnt 438</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 84; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 17</P1></P>
<P>58. There have been various formulations of guidelines to be used by appellate courts in deciding whether a trial judge has gone too far in expressing an opinion. In <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Garofoli</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court of Appeal stated that an appellate court may find that the trial judge has crossed the boundary, even though the jury was told that they were not bound by his views on the evidence, if:
<P1>1) the opinion expressed is far stronger than that facts warrant; or</P1>
<P1>2) the opinion is expressed so strongly that there is a likelihood that the jury would be overawed by it.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Garofoli</SOC><CITE>1988 CarswellOnt 68</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 111, reversed on other grounds [1990] 2 S.C.R. 1421 (S.C.C.); Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 18</P1></P>
<P>59. In <CASEREF><SOC>McFarlane v. Safadi</SOC></CASEREF> the Court of Appeal considered, amongst other things, whether the trial judge's charge had been balanced and fair. The Court stated:
<QUOTE><P>31. The hallmark of a fair trial is that the judge preside with impartiality and neutrality between the parties. The judge must not cross the line and become a participant in the litigation. When he or she does so, his or her impartiality and neutrality are lost. It is at that moment that the trial ceases to be fair.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>39 The trial judge advised the jury in his charge that, &ldquo;If you come to a conclusion that some of my questions indicated that I had a particular opinion as to the facts of this case, then I ask you and I invite you just to ignore any views that you have as to what I might think.&rdquo; Whether such an instruction was sufficient is questionable. However, its effect was significantly reduced by his subsequent return to his strong criticism of the police officer's failure to conduct a thorough accident investigation.</P>
<P>40 In my view, based on the comments of the trial judge, the jury would have had a very difficult time coming to any conclusion other than that the police officer had failed to do his duty and, had he not done so, he would likely have come to a different conclusion concerning Mr. Hansen's liability.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>McFarlane v. Safadi</SOC><CITE>2004 CarswellOnt 1696</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 19</P1></P>
<P>60. The jury must remain the arbiter of the facts, such that any comments made by the trial judge cannot amount to a rebuttal of a party's address to the jury or unfairly denigrate or undermine the position of a party.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Lawes</SOC><CITE>2006 CarswellOnt 1072</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 23; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 20</P1></P>
<P>61. Comments made by judges expressing disbelief or skepticism regarding a party's position or appearing to adopt an adversarial position towards a party can certainly raise a reasonable apprehension that the judge's mind was closed to an impartial view of a party's case. That kind of conduct destroys the image of impartiality that must exist in a courtroom.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Sorger v. Bank of Nova Scotia</SOC><CITE>1998 CarswellOnt 2108</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras 5 and 8-9; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 21</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Shoppers Mortgage and Loan Corporation v. Health First Wellington Square</SOC><CITE>1995 CarswellOnt 350</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 21; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 22</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Lennox v. Arbor Memorial Services Inc.</SOC><CITE>2001 CarswellOnt 4248</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 12; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 23</P1></P>
<P>62. A judge's viewpoint has the potential to unduly influence a jury. Charge instructions that either directly or indirectly directed the jury to a conclusion inimical to the appellant are beyond what a judge should be permitted to do as a neutral arbitrator of the process. In concatenating distinct pieces of evidence as he did (such as juxtaposing the dates when Alan received nerve block injections with the dates when he was observed on surveillance), the trial judge, in effect, became a protagonist for the respondents.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>The jury verdict was inordinately low.</TI>
<P>63. An appellate court will overturn a jury's verdict where the Court is satisfied that the verdict is one that a properly instructed jury, acting judicially, could not reasonably have rendered. If the re has been a miscarriage of justice or a substantial wrong, the jury's verdict cannot stand.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Barker v. Zurich Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2001 CarswellOnt 358</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 26; Appellant's Brief of Authorities Tab 24</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Koukounakis et al v. Stainrod et al</SOC><CITE>1995 CarswellOnt 449</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 10; Appellants' Book of Authorities, Tab 25</P1></P>
<P>64. This Court has stated that:
<QUOTE><P>Normally this Court, depending on the amount of damages, takes the view that if it is of the opinion that the award is too high or too low by 50 per cent, it concludes that the damages are inordinately high or low and varies it accordingly or directs a new trial if it is a jury verdict.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Howes v Crosby</SOC><CITE>1984 CarswellOnt 695</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 47, Appellant's Brief of Authorities, Tab 26</P1></P>
<P>65. Having regard to the extent of Alan's injuries and, in particular his bilateral shoulder surgeries, the jury's award of $3,000.00 for pain and suffering is grossly inadequate, such as to constitute a miscarriage of justice such that appellate intervention is warranted. A chart setting out damages awarded to plaintiffs with complaints similar to those of Alan is attached as Schedule &ldquo;F.&rdquo;</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>E.</N><TI>On an appeal from an award for damages for personal injury, the court may, if it considers it just, substitute its own assessment of damages.</TI>
<P>66. On an appeal from an award for damages for personal injury, the court may, if it considers it just, substitute its own assessment of damages.
<P1><EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, as amended, c. C43, s. 119.</P1></P>
<P>67. Where the fairness of the trial is not in issue, and the jury appears simply to have arrived at an inappropriate assessment on the evidence, the interest in avoiding the delay and expense of a new trial would seem to weigh in favour of the appellate court substituting its own assessment.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Padfield v. Martin</SOC><CITE>2003 CarswellOnt 1819</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 56, Appellant's Brief of Authorities, Tab 27</P1></P>
<P>68. In <CASEREF><SOC>Pilon v. Janveaux</SOC></CASEREF>, the jury was inadvertently not asked to apportion the degree of fault as between the various defendants. The Court of Appeal decided that it was appropriate that it apportion liability, concluding that:
<QUOTE><P>[T]he interests of justice require that a new trial be avoided if possible. Memories will be stale, and the cost is prohibitive. Instead, this court should perform the apportionment task that the jury ought to have been instructed to and did not perform. (para. 31)</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Pilon v. Janveaux</SOC><CITE>2005 CarswellOnt 5660</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 31; Appellant's Brief of Authorities, Tab 28</P1></P>
<P>69. Although a litigant has a substantive right to have his or her case heard by a jury, that right is not absolute.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gorman v. Falardeau</SOC><CITE>2005 CarswellOnt 2214</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 33; Appellant's Brief of Authorities, Tab 29</P1></P>
<P>70. Access to justice in a timely manner is a right at least as fundamental and important to a plaintiff as trial by jury is to a defendant.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Trisect Construction Corp.</SOC><CITE>2016 CarswellOnt 782</CITE><COURTJUR>SCJ</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 11; Appellant's Brief of Authorities, Tab 30</P1></P>
<P>71. In <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court Canada, in the context of summary judgment motions, endorsed the principle that that access to justice will sometimes require more expeditious manners of resolving disputes than a full trial procedure. Karakatsanis J., writing for the unanimous Court, directed:
<QUOTE><P>Ensuring access to justice is the greatest challenge to the rule of law in Canada today. Trials have become increasingly expensive and protracted. Most Canadians cannot afford to sue when they are wronged or defend themselves when they are sued, and cannot afford to go to trial. Without an effective and accessible means of enforcing rights, the rule of law is threatened. Without public adjudication of civil cases, the development of the common law is stunted.</P>
<P>Increasingly, there is recognition that a culture shift is required in order to create an environment promoting timely and affordable access to the civil justice system.</P>
<P>This shift entails simplifying pre-trial procedures and moving the emphasis away from the conventional trial in favour of proportional procedures tailored to the needs of the particular case. The balance between procedure and access struck by our justice system must come to reflect modem reality and recognize that new models of adjudication can be fair and just.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 CarswellOnt 641</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at paras 1 and 2; Appellant's Brief of Authorities, Tab 31</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>F.</N><TI>The trial judge was required by law to determine whether Alan's claim passed the threshold.</TI>
<P>72. Section 267.5(15) if the <EM>Insurance Act</EM>, supra, requires that, in the absence of a motion before trial, the trial judge <BOLD>must</BOLD> determine whether a plaintiff is entitled claim non-pecuniary damages arising from a motor vehicle accident:
<QUOTE><P>(15) If no motion is made under subsection (12)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>(12) In an action for loss or damage from bodily injury or death arising directly or indirectly from the use or operation of an automobile, a judge shall, on motion made before trial with the consent of the parties or in accordance with an order of a judge who conducts a pre-trial conference, determine for the purpose of subsections (3) and (5) whether, as a result of the use or operation of the automobile, the injured person has died or has sustained,</P>
<P>(a) permanent serious disfigurement; or</P>
<P>(b) permanent serious impairment of an important physical, mental or psychological function.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, the trial judge shall determine for the purpose of subsections (3) and (5) whether, as a result of the use or operation of the automobile, the injured person has died or has sustained,
<P1>(a) permanent serious disfigurement; or</P1>
<P1>(b) permanent serious impairment of an important physical, mental or psychological function.</P1></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>73. The Appellant had the onus of demonstrating that he had suffered a &ldquo;permanent serious impairment of an important physical, mental or psychological function&rdquo; under subsection 267.5(3) and (5) of <EM>the Insurance Act</EM>, supra. Section 4.2(1) of the <EM>Court Proceedings for Automobile Accidents that Occur on or After November 1, 1996</EM> sets out the criteria that must be met in order for the court to make such a finding. Section 4.2(1)1, which contains the requirements for a &ldquo;serious&rdquo; impairment, provides:
<QUOTE><P>1. The impairment must,</P>
<P>i. Substantially interfere with the person's ability to continue his or her regular or usual employment, despite reasonable efforts to accommodate the person's impairment and the person's reasonable efforts to use the accommodation to allow the person to continue employment,</P>
<P>ii. Substantially interfere with the person's ability to continue training for a career in a field in which the person was being trained before the incident, despite reasonable efforts to accommodate the person's impairment and the person's reasonable efforts to use the accommodation to allow the person to continue his or her career training, or</P>
<P>iii. Substantially interfere with the most of the usual activities of daily living, considering the person's age.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>74. Having regard to his Accident related functional impairments, including an inability to work, Alan met the test established by section 267.5 of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> for entitlement to sue the respondents.</P>
<P>75. Contrary to section 267.5(15), Justice Myers declined to decide whether Alan had been left with &ldquo;threshold impairments&rdquo; on the basis that he considered the issue to be moot.</P>
<P>76. The <EM>Interpretation Act</EM>, R.S.C. 1985, c. 1&ndash;21, section 11 provides:
<QUOTE><P>The expression &ldquo;shall&rdquo; is to be construed as imperative and the expression &ldquo;may&rdquo; as permissive.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>77. As noted by Ruth Sullivan in <EM>Sullivan and Driedger on the Construction of Statutes</EM>, 3<SUP>rd</SUP> ed. (1991), at page 60:
<QUOTE><P>When &ldquo;shall&rdquo; and &ldquo;must&rdquo; are used in legislation to impose an obligation or create a prohibition or requirement, they are always imperative. A person who &ldquo;shall&rdquo; or &ldquo;must&rdquo; do something has no discretion to decide whether or not to do it.</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="VI">PART V&mdash;Order sought</TI>
<P>78. The appellant respectfully seeks:
<P1>a) an order setting aside the judgment entered in accordance with the verdict of the jury and in its place the appellant seeks a judgment for an increased verdict;</P1>
<P1>b) In the alternative, an order requiring a new trial;</P1>
<P1>c) Costs of the action and appeal.</P1></P>
<P>July 12, 2017</P>
<P>All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
